<h4>
    The Electronic Charge
</h4>

<p>
    In a previous unit, charge was measured in a very arbitrary seeming unit
    called a "Coulomb."
    In actuality, electric charge comes from protons and electrons.
    A single proton has a charge of \( +1.602 \times 10^{-19} \text{ Coulombs} \).
    A single electron has a charge of \( -1.602 \times 10^{-19} \text{ Coulombs} \).
    This value is called the <strong>elementary charge</strong> and is represented by the symbol \( e \).
    $$
    1 e = 1.602 \times 10^{-19} \text{ Coulombs}
    $$
</p>

